`crates/ctx-cage/tests/` is the integration-test suite for `ctx-cage`, validating the sandbox-launch and API-proxy machinery end-to-end against the crate's public surface (`bwrap::build_bwrap_args`, `lifecycle::load_cagevars`, `cli::resolve_mode`, `proxy`) rather than its internals. Depending on this directory buys you no code — it's a correctness gate that must pass before touching sandbox argv construction, DNS/network isolation, env-var precedence, CLI mode resolution, or proxy header rewriting.

Several files encode ADR-driven invariants that only manifest as runtime hangs or security holes, not compile errors: ADR-046 (workspace bound at its real host path, not `/work`) and ADR-049 (DNS must resolve through a bound `resolv.conf`, and its embedded nameservers must include at least one non-loopback entry) span `bwrap_build.rs` and `cage_assets.rs` — changing the resolv.conf asset or the bind logic requires re-checking both. `proxy.rs` encodes a similar operational invariant: proxy errors must go to a log file, never stderr, because stderr is the live PTY during interactive cage runs.

A shared test-infra pattern recurs across files: atomic-counter-based unique tempfile/tempdir/socket naming (`cagevars.rs`, `cli.rs`, `proxy.rs`) to survive parallel test execution, with manual (not `Drop`-based) cleanup — panics mid-test can leak tempfiles/sockets. `cli.rs`'s `base()` helper hardcodes the `Cli`/`TaskFlags`/`SpendFlags` field layout, so adding a CLI field requires updating this test file or the build breaks.

No file here mocks `ctx_cage` internals broadly; each targets one public function or asset with real inputs (real tempfiles, real Unix sockets, real embedded strings), making this suite the actual behavioral spec for those contracts.